<section class="intro-slide">
  <h1 id="events">Events</h1>

  <h3 id="csci-ua0480-001">CSCI-UA.0480-001</h3>

  <p><small></small></p>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="events-1">Events</h2>

  <p>We can have JavaScript run whenever a specific even happens.  We&#39;ll use <strong><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/EventTarget.addEventListener">document.addEventListener</a></strong> to monitor for events.</p>

  <ul>
    <li>it takes two parameters&#8230;</li>
    <li>an event as a string (<a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Events">see some event types in the mdn docs for events</a>)</li>
    <li>the name of a function that should run when the event is triggered:</li>
  </ul>

  <p><br /></p>
  <pre><code data-trim="" contenteditable="">
// calls the function called main once the DOM has fully loaded
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', main);
</code></pre>

</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="events-types">Events Types</h2>

  <p>We&#39;ll be using these two (out of the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Events">many available</a>):</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>click</strong> - triggered on mouse click (press and release) on a single element</li>
    <li><strong>DOMContentLoaded</strong> - document has been completed loaded and parsed (without waiting for CSS, images, etc.)</li>
  </ul>

  <p><br /></p>

  <p><strong>The callback function receives an <code>event</code> object&#8230;</strong> &#8594;</p>

  <ul>
    <li>contains useful information</li>
    <li>such as the x and y position of where the mouse was clicked</li>
    <li><strong>this in the callback refers to the element clicked!</strong></li>
  </ul>

</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="handling-clicks">Handling Clicks</h2>

  <p><strong>Make all of the paragraph links clickable&#8230; and change the text of the paragraph to the position of the mouse</strong> &#8594;</p>

  <pre><code data-trim="" contenteditable="">
function handleClick(event) {
	this.textContent = event.x + ',' + event.y;
}

var p = document.getElementsByTagName('p');
for (var i = 0; i &lt; p.length; i++) {
	p[i].addEventListener('click', handleClick);
}
</code></pre>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="where-does-this-code-live">Where Does This Code Live?</h2>

  <p>So, now that you have code:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>that registers an event listener&#8230;</li>
    <li>and specifies a function that handles the event</li>
  </ul>

  <p><br />
<strong>What are some criteria for where this stuff should live?</strong> &#8594;</p>

  <ul class="fragment">
    <li>probably in an external file</li>
    <li>perhaps at the end of the body</li>
    <li>and maybe we could even use that <code>DOMContentLoaded</code> event, right?</li>
  </ul>
</section>
